# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dragonfly-db
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:dragonfly-db/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] Dragonfly is specifically optimized to operate in cloud environments.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] It is officially supported and certified for use on both x86_64 and arm64 architectures.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] For x86_64 architectures, Dragonfly requires a minimum *sandybridge* architecture to function properly.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] To ensure compatibility and performance, Dragonfly undergoes continuous testing on various cloud platforms.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] These include Graviton2 instances in AWS cloud, as well as x86_64 based instances in both AWS and GCP clouds.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] Furthermore, Dragonfly's regression tests, which can be found here, are continously run on Azure cloud via GitHub Actions.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] This helps guarantee the reliability and stability of the software.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] Dragonfly is compatible with Linux versions 4.14 or later.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] However, to achieve optimal performance, it is recommended to run Dragonfly on kernel version 5.10 or later.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] The Dragonfly build environment is based on Ubuntu 20.04.
[src:dragonfly-db/getting-started] Learn how to measure the performance of Dragonfly in a cloud environment.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:dragonfly-db/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] A **key-value database**, or **key-value store**, is a data storage paradigm designed for storing, retrieving, and managing associative arrays, a data structure more commonly known today as a *dictionary*.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Dictionaries contain a collection of *objects*, or *records*, which in turn have many different *fields* within them.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] These records are stored and retrieved using a *key* that uniquely identifies the record, and is used to find the data within the database.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Key-value databases differ from the better known relational databases (RDB).
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] RDBs pre-define the data structure in the database as a series of tables containing fields with well-defined data types.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Exposing the data types to the database program allows it to apply various optimizations.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] In contrast, key-value systems treat the value as opaque to the database itself, and typically support only simple operations such as storing, retrieving, updating, and deleting a value by its key.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] This offers considerable flexibility and makes such systems well suited to low-latency, high-throughput workloads dominated by direct key lookups, but less suitable for applications that require complex queries or explicit relationships among records.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] A lack of standardization, limited transaction support, and relatively simple query interfaces long restricted many key-value systems to specialized uses, but the rapid move to cloud computing after 2010 helped drive renewed interest in them as part of the broader NoSQL movement.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Some graph databases, such as ArangoDB, are also key–value databases internally, adding the concept of relationships (*pointers*) between records as a first-class data type.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Key–value systems span a wide consistency spectrum, from eventually consistent designs to strongly consistent or serializable ones, and some allow the consistency level to be configured as part of the trade-off against latency and availability.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Renewed interest in key–value and other NoSQL systems was driven in part by the demands of big data, distributed, and cloud applications.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Their scalability and availability made them attractive for cloud data management, although limited transaction support, low-level query interfaces, and the lack of standardization remained obstacles to wider adoption.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Some maintain data in memory (RAM), while others employ solid-state drives or rotating disks.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Some key–value systems add additional structure to their keys.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] For example, Oracle NoSQL Database organizes records using composite keys with "major" and "minor" components, an arrangement that Oracle compares to a directory-path structure in a file system.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] More generally, however, key–value stores are defined by their use of unique keys associated with opaque values and by their emphasis on simple key-based operations.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Unix included *dbm* (database manager), a minimal database library written by Ken Thompson for managing associative arrays with a single key and hash-based access.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Later implementations and related libraries included sdbm, GNU dbm (gdbm), and Berkeley DB.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] A more recent example is RocksDB, a persistent key–value storage engine developed at Facebook and designed for large-scale applications.
[src:dragonfly-db/key-value-database] Other examples include in-memory systems such as Memcached and Redis, and persistent systems such as Berkeley DB, Riak, and Voldemort.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly is an in-memory data store built for modern application workloads.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Fully compatible with Redis and Memcached APIs, Dragonfly requires no code changes to adopt.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Compared to legacy in-memory datastores, Dragonfly delivers 25X more throughput, higher cache hit rates with lower tail latency, and can run on up to 80% less resources for the same sized workload.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] We first compare Dragonfly with Redis on `m5.large` instance which is commonly used to run Redis due to its single-threaded architecture.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The benchmark above shows that the algorithmic layer inside DF that allows it to scale vertically does not take a large toll when running single-threaded.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] However, if we take a bit stronger instance (m5.xlarge), the gap between DF and Redis starts growing.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly throughput capacity continues to grow with instance size, while single-threaded Redis is bottlenecked on CPU and reaches local maxima in terms of performance.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] If we compare Dragonfly and Redis on the most network-capable instance c6gn.16xlarge, Dragonfly showed a 25X increase in throughput compared to Redis single process, crossing 3.8M QPS.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] In pipeline mode `--pipeline=30`, Dragonfly reaches **10M QPS** for SET and **15M QPS** for GET operations.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] We compared Dragonfly with Memcached on a c6gn.16xlarge instance on AWS.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] With a comparable latency, Dragonfly throughput outperformed Memcached throughput in both write and read workloads.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly demonstrated better latency in write workloads due to contention on the write path in Memcached.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Memcached exhibited lower latency for the read benchmark, but also lower throughput.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] To test memory efficiency, we filled Dragonfly and Redis with ~5GB of data using the `debug populate 5000000 key 1024` command, sent update traffic with `memtier`, and kicked off the snapshotting with the `bgsave` command.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] This figure demonstrates how each server behaved in terms of memory efficiency.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly was 30% more memory efficient than Redis in the idle state and did not show any visible increase in memory use during the snapshot phase.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] At peak, Redis memory use increased to almost 3X that of Dragonfly.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly finished the snapshot faster, within a few seconds.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] For more info about memory efficiency in Dragonfly, see our Dashtable doc.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly supports common Redis arguments where applicable.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] For example, you can run: `dragonfly --requirepass=foo --bind localhost`.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] For more options like logs management or TLS support, run `dragonfly --help`.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly currently supports ~185 Redis commands and all Memcached commands besides `cas`.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Almost on par with the Redis 5 API, Dragonfly's next milestone will be to stabilize basic functionality and implement the replication API.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] If there is a command you need that is not implemented yet, please open an issue.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] For Dragonfly-native replication, we are designing a distributed log format that will support order-of-magnitude higher speeds.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Following the replication feature, we will continue adding missing commands for Redis versions 3-6 APIs.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Please see our Command Reference for the current commands supported by Dragonfly.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly has a single, unified, adaptive caching algorithm that is simple and memory efficient.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] You can enable caching mode by passing the `--cache_mode=true` flag.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Once this mode is on, Dragonfly will evict items least likely to be stumbled upon in the future but only when it is near the `maxmemory` limit.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Expiration ranges are limited to ~8 years.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Expiration deadlines with millisecond precision (PEXPIRE, PSETEX, etc.) are rounded to the closest second **for deadlines greater than 2^28ms**, which has less than 0.001% error and should be acceptable for large ranges.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] If this is not suitable for your use case, get in touch or open an issue explaining your case.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] For more detailed differences between Dragonfly expiration deadlines and Redis implementations, see here.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] By default, Dragonfly allows HTTP access via its main TCP port (6379).
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] That's right, you can connect to Dragonfly via Redis protocol and via HTTP protocol — the server recognizes the protocol automatically during the connection initiation.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] HTTP access currently does not have much info but will include useful debugging and management info in the future.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Go to the URL `:6379/metrics` to view Prometheus-compatible metrics.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The Prometheus exported metrics are compatible with the Grafana dashboard, see here.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The HTTP console is meant to be accessed within a safe network.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] If you expose Dragonfly's TCP port externally, we advise you to disable the console with `--http_admin_console=false` or `--nohttp_admin_console`.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Dragonfly started as an experiment to see how an in-memory datastore could look if it was designed in 2022.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Based on lessons learned from our experience as users of memory stores and engineers who worked for cloud companies, we knew that we need to preserve two key properties for Dragonfly: Atomicity guarantees for all operations and low, sub-millisecond latency over very high throughput.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Our first challenge was how to fully utilize CPU, memory, and I/O resources using servers that are available today in public clouds.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] To solve this, we use shared-nothing architecture, which allows us to partition the keyspace of the memory store between threads so that each thread can manage its own slice of dictionary data.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The library that powers thread and I/O management for shared-nothing architecture is open-sourced here.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] To provide atomicity guarantees for multi-key operations, we use the advancements from recent academic research.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] We chose the paper "VLL: a lock manager redesign for main memory database systems” to develop the transactional framework for Dragonfly.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The choice of shared-nothing architecture and VLL allowed us to compose atomic multi-key operations without using mutexes or spinlocks.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] This was a major milestone for our PoC and its performance stood out from other commercial and open-source solutions.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Our second challenge was to engineer more efficient data structures for the new store.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] To achieve this goal, we based our core hashtable structure on the paper "Dash: Scalable Hashing on Persistent Memory".
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The paper itself is centered around the persistent memory domain and is not directly related to main-memory stores, but it's still most applicable to our problem.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] The hashtable design suggested in the paper allowed us to maintain two special properties that are present in the Redis dictionary: The incremental hashing ability during datastore growth the ability to traverse the dictionary under changes using a stateless scan operation.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] In addition to these two properties, Dash is more efficient in CPU and memory use.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] Once we had built the foundation for Dragonfly and we were happy with its performance, we went on to implement the Redis and Memcached functionality.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] We have to date implemented ~185 Redis commands (roughly equivalent to Redis 5.0 API) and 13 Memcached commands.
[src:dragonfly-db/main-readme-md] And finally, *Our mission is to build a well-designed, ultra-fast, cost-efficient in-memory datastore for cloud workloads that takes advantage of the latest hardware advancements.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] Dragonfly is a modern in-memory datastore, fully compatible with Redis and Memcached APIs.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] Dragonfly implements novel algorithms and data structures on top of a multi-threaded, shared-nothing architecture.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] As a result, Dragonfly reaches 25X performance compared to Redis and supports millions of QPS on a single instance.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] Dragonfly is fully compatible with the Redis ecosystem and requires no code changes to implement.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] (A graph comparing performance of Redis vs.
[src:dragonfly-db/page] Visit the getting started section to explore deployment options and try Dragonfly yourself.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The project was developed and maintained by Salvatore Sanfilippo, starting in 2009.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] From 2015 until 2020, he led a project core team sponsored by Redis Labs.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Salvatore Sanfilippo left Redis as the maintainer in 2020.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In 2021 Redis Labs dropped the Labs from its name and now is known simply as "Redis".
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In 2018, some modules for Redis adopted a modified Apache 2.0 license with a Commons Clause.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In 2024, the main Redis code switched from the open-source BSD-3 license to being dual-licensed under the Redis Source Available License v2 and the Server Side Public License v1.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] On May 1, 2025, Redis became tri-licensed beginning with version 8.0, with the GNU Affero General Public License as the third option.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The name *Redis* means Remote Dictionary Server.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The Redis project began when Salvatore Sanfilippo (nicknamed *antirez*) was trying to improve the scalability of his Italian startup and developed a real-time web log analyzer.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] After encountering significant problems in scaling some types of workloads using traditional database systems, Sanfilippo began in 2009 to prototype a first proof of concept version of Redis in Tcl.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Later, Sanfilippo translated that prototype to the C language and implemented the first data type, the list.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] After a few weeks of using the project internally with success, Sanfilippo decided to open source it, announcing the project on Hacker News.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The project began to get traction, particularly among the Ruby community, with GitHub and Instagram being among the first companies adopting it.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Sanfilippo was hired by VMware in March 2010.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In May 2013, Redis was sponsored by Pivotal Software (a VMware spin-off).
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In June 2015, development became sponsored by Redis Ltd.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] This made the modules source-available and no longer free software.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The core Redis software remained under a BSD license, with Redis Ltd. committing to maintaining these terms.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In October 2018, Redis 5.0 was released, introducing Redis Stream – a new data structure that allows storage of multiple fields and string values with an automatic, time-based sequence at a single key.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In June 2020, Salvatore Sanfilippo stepped down as Redis' sole maintainer.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Sanfilippo was succeeded by Yossi Gottlieb and Oran Agra.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In March 2024, Redis Ltd. announced that beginning with version 7.4, the core Redis software would be relicensed under the RSAL and Server Side Public License (SSPL), both of which are source-available and non-free.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The Linux Foundation subsequently announced that it would fork the last BSD-licensed version of Redis as Valkey.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In May 2025, Redis Ltd. announced that it would change the license again to the AGPL beginning on version 8.0, citing that forks had achieved their goal of creating a "level playing field" of differentiated products, and that Redis has achieved "record growth" since the change in license.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Sanfilippo returned to Redis in December 2024.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis is a system that functions as both a data store and a cache.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Data is modified and read from the main computer memory while also being persisted to disk in a format optimized for sequential access rather than random access.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The formatted data is only reconstructed into memory once the system restarts.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis uses a data model that differs from relational database management system (RDBMS).
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Commands specify operations on abstract data types rather than queries to be executed by a database engine.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Data is stored in structures designed for direct retrieval.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] It does not rely on secondary indexes, aggregations, or other features common in traditional RDBMS.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The Redis implementation uses the fork system call to duplicate the process holding the data.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] This allows the parent process to continue serving clients while the child process persists the in-memory data to disk.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis supports a number of data types including Strings, JavaScript Object Notation (JSON) documents, Hashes (a collection of fields, each field is a name-value string pair), lists, sets, vector sets, and more.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The Redis Query Engine allows users to use Redis as a document database, a vector database, a secondary index, and a search engine.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] With Redis Query Engine, users can define indexes for hash and JSON documents, and use a rich query language for vector search, full-text search, geospatial queries, and aggregations.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis Pub/Sub (short for publish/subscribe) is a lightweight messaging capability.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Publishers send messages to a channel, and subscribers receive messages from that channel.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] A Redis transaction allows the execution of a group of commands in a single step.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] A request sent by another client will never be served during the execution of a transaction.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] This guarantees that the commands are executed as a single isolated operation.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis users can also upload and execute Lua scripts on the server.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] As of May 1, 2025, for all version of Redis starting with 8.0, all data types are included in the same package and available under the Redis Source Available license v2.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Previously some data types were separate and therefore available under difference licenses.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis typically holds the whole dataset in memory.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Versions up to 2.4 could be configured to use what they refer to as virtual memory in which some of the dataset is stored on disk, but this feature is deprecated.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis can rewrite the append-only file in the background to avoid an indefinite growth of the journal.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Journaling was introduced in version 1.1 and is generally considered the safer approach.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] By default, Redis writes data to a file system at least every two seconds, with more or less robust options available if needed.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] In the case of a complete system failure on default settings, only a few seconds of data will be lost.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis supports master–replica replication.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Data from any Redis server can replicate to any number of replicas.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] A replica may be a master to another replica.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] This allows Redis to implement a single-rooted replication tree.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis replicas can be configured to accept writes, permitting intentional and unintentional inconsistency between instances.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The publish–subscribe feature is fully implemented, so a client of a replica may subscribe to a channel and receive a full feed of messages published to the master, anywhere up the replication tree.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Replication is useful for read (but not write) scalability or data redundancy.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] When the durability of data is not needed, the in-memory nature of Redis allows it to perform well compared to database systems that write every change to disk before considering a transaction committed.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis operates as a single process and is single-threaded or double-threaded when it rewrites the AOF (append-only file).
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Thus, a single Redis instance cannot use parallel execution of tasks such as stored procedures.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis introduced clustering in April 2015 with the release of version 3.0.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The cluster specification implements a subset of Redis commands: all single-key commands are available, multi-key operations (commands related to unions and intersections) are restricted to keys belonging to the same node, and commands related to database selection operations are unavailable.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] A Redis cluster can scale up to 1,000 nodes, achieve "acceptable" write safety and to continue operations when some nodes fail.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis has been used by Adobe, Airbnb, Amazon, Hulu, OpenAI, Salesforce, Shopify, Tinder, Twitter, and Yahoo.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Typical use cases of Redis are session caching, full page cache, message queue applications, leaderboards and counting among others.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] The publish–subscribe messaging paradigm allows real-time communication between servers.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Amazon Web Services offers a managed Redis service called ElastiCache for Redis, Google offers a managed Redis service called Cloud Memorystore, Microsoft offers Azure Cache for Redis in Azure, and Alibaba offers ApsaraDB for Redis in Alibaba Cloud.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] Redis is interfaced with by various libraries.
[src:dragonfly-db/redis] For example, POCO C++ Libraries supports interfacing with Redis through its `Poco::Redis` library.
